wcg_diff_general: There was no difference, except a small cow killer ant began walking toward me on my desk which interrupted me for a few seconds while I plucked it away. There was literally no difference whatsoever. The only difference was halfway through the first word chain game, I realized I didn't need to actually type unrelated words, just whatever popped into my head, as long as they didn't make a sentence.
wcg_strategy: For the first half of the first game I was trying to type unrelated words to avoid writing a sentence, so I would usually enter the second word that entered my mind. After that it was just whatever. Sometimes I typed a synonym of the previous word. Sometimes I typed a word related to the previous one via a common theme; e.g. Lord of the Rings. Sometimes I looked around me in my room and typed whatever I saw; e.g. spoon.  Sometimes during the first half of the first game I noticed my next word began with the same letter, but this was unconsciously.
guess_experiment: I think the experiment already said it was trying to measure something like neural and cognitive brain processes that occur during reading a story.
volition_explanation: Most of the time, during the word chain game, I was sulking over a personal family matter that irritated me greatly, and which had occurred earlier today. But the rest of the time was interspersed with unintentional flashbacks from the story, and I was also thinking about how I hated that the sentences were removed individually from their surrounding quotation marks if the quote was longer than one sentence, and this made it very difficult to follow who was talking. So I was confused about some aspects of the story. For example, I'm still not clear whether the husband was the murderer of the girl at the campsite or not.
wcg_diff_explanation: I think the word chain game acted as a form of meditation which allowed the morbid conflict from earlier today to gain prominence in my mind and this was very distressing.
interference_explanation: This story was my favorite because it is actually relevant to my life. For example, my own lightbulb was growing dim and I didn't even realize how dim it was until my brother gave me a new one that was even brighter than mine was brand new.
volition_interference_explanation: Well, because of where I'm situated in my room, I can almost see my own lightbulb out the corner of my eye and the story provoked flashbacks of my brother replacing my lightbulb with a super bright one. Also the fan reminded of the fan in my living room (which also has a lightbulb in the center) and the remote made me think of my grandfather struggling to learn how to use the smart TV remote.
open_box: Taking single sentences out of their surrounding quotes (when the quote was multiple sentences long) was very confusing and me lose track of who was speaking more than once.  Also, I had to get up to run to the bathroom right before answering the questions about the purple story. I also grabbed some pineapple and cottage cheese out the fridge on the way back to eat while I completed the survey because I was starving (not literally).
